{"author":"Joe Oakhart","author_email":"joeoakhart+bot@navapbc.com","author_id":"594c-9dcf-5ad6-4e6d","author_sig":"{\"payload\": \"\", \"payloadType\": \"application/vnd.rebar.authorship.v1+json\", \"signatures\": [{\"keyid\": \"594c-9dcf-5ad6-4e6d\", \"sig\": \"\"}]}","data":{"fields":{"description":"## What\nThe going-forward compact metrics snapshot: a small JSON record appended per CI run (and readable by the command) persisting point-in-time code-health numbers whose history is otherwise ephemeral — coverage %, complexity distribution, clone count — so their movement accrues.\n\n## Files\n- `src/rebar/metrics/snapshot.py` — new: `write_snapshot(dict)` appends a timestamped record to a committed NDJSON file; `read_snapshots(since,until)` yields in-range records for the registry.\n- `.gitignore` — add `!.rebar/metrics-snapshots.ndjson` to surgically un-ignore the store. The repo gitignores ALL `.rebar/` contents via a blanket `.rebar/*` rule (line 20) and tracks specific files with per-file `!`-negations (e.g. `!.rebar/criteria_routing.json`); WITHOUT this negation line the snapshot file is silently gitignored and the series never persists.\n- `.rebar/metrics-snapshots.ndjson` — new committed artifact (one snapshot per line). **It lives under the tracked `.rebar/` store, NOT under `reports/`**: `/reports/` is gitignored (`.gitignore:74`), so a snapshot file there would never be committed and the trend series would silently never accumulate. `.rebar/` is already tracked in git (e.g. `.rebar/criteria_routing.json`), so snapshots persist and sync.\n- `tests/unit/metrics/test_snapshot.py` — new.\n\n## Approach\nCoverage/complexity/clone are computed at a point in time; their trend needs a stored series, which does not exist today. An append-only NDJSON snapshot (not a new event type) is the lowest-friction durable store; it lives under the tracked `.rebar/` store so it is committed and synced (unlike the gitignored `reports/`, which holds only ephemeral CI artifacts). The command reads it for trend metrics, and until a snapshot exists a metric reports `unavailable`. Append-only and additive.\n\n## Tests\n- Unit: `write_snapshot` then `read_snapshots` round-trips; a range filter excludes out-of-range records; a malformed line is skipped without raising.\n\n## Acceptance Criteria\n- [ ] `tests/unit/metrics/test_snapshot.py` passes: a written snapshot is read back within its date range (`assert rec in read_snapshots(since,until)`) and excluded outside it.\n- [ ] a corrupt/truncated NDJSON line is skipped and the reader still returns the valid records — unit test asserts count equals the valid-record count.\n- [ ] the snapshot store path is `.rebar/metrics-snapshots.ndjson` (a git-tracked path), verified by the test writing under `.rebar/` and asserting the file is not matched by the repo's `.gitignore` — so the going-forward series actually persists."}},"env_id":"ade0f2ef-51cc-45a2-bb97-c09846cd3df5","event_type":"EDIT","timestamp":1784439004828558001,"uuid":"800de214-cd94-4f85-84f1-028a7ae0931a"}